33333><table border=0 width=100% cellpadding=5 cellspacing=1><tr><td valign=top background=http://home.earthlink.net/~nsmessageboard/ezboard/images/bar.jpg class=headings><font color=#FFFFFF>Author</font></td><td valign=top background=http://home.earthlink.net/~nsmessageboard/ezboard/images/bar.jpg class=headings><font color=#FFFFFF>Comment</font></td></tr><tr bgcolor=#484848><td nowrap width=20% valign=top align=left><span class=title> <A HREF=http://pub97.ezboard.com/umauk2.showPublicProfile?language=EN>Mauk2</A></span><br> <span class=usertitle>Space Tourist</span><br>  Posts: 11<br> <font color=#6F6F6F>(9/9/02 11:30:54 pm)</font><br>   <a href=http://pub97.ezboard.com/fnuclearspacefrm1.showAddReplyScreenFromWeb?topicID=513.topic&index=61>Reply</a>   </td><td valign=top align=left class=m><span class=title>   Re: Interstellar daydreams</span><hr size=1> cool website, John Fraz.<br>
<br>
As threatened, I posted my thoughts for a NTR powered launcher.  I did not want to pull this thread off topic, so I put it in <!--EZCODE LINK START--><a href="http://pub97.ezboard.com/fnuclearspacefrm4.showMessage?topicID=133.topic"> this one </a><!--EZCODE LINK END--> instead.<br>
<br>
As a note, if you are going to go interstellar without breaking the laws of physics too much, a lightsail boosted antimatter powered design using a magnetic ramscoop to gain reaction mass from the interstellar medium is the way to go in my opinion.   Use the lasers on the light sail to get to .4 or .5 c, dump the sail, accelerate to .7 c using antimatter.  Then deploy the ramscoop to sweep up more reaction mass and start decelerating, then use the antimatter rocket to stop at the end.<br>
<br>
The trip back is slower, since you only have onboard power to make the trip.<br>
<br>
With an outbound average speed of .5 c and an average return speed of .2 c a round trip to a star up to 10 lightyears away should be doable in less than 60 years.<br>
<br>
Not too shabby! <p></p><i>Edited by: <A HREF=http://pub97.ezboard.com/umauk2.showPublicProfile?language=EN>Mauk2</A> at: 9/14/02 2:48:00 am<br></i></td></tr><tr bgcolor=#333333><td nowrap width=20% valign=top align=left><span class=title> <A HREF=http://pub97.ezboard.com/uarkuunaves.showPublicProfile?language=EN>ArkuunAves</A></span><br> <span class=usertitle>NEP Freighter Crewman</span><br>  Posts: 84<br> <font color=#6F6F6F>(9/10/02 12:55:22 am)</font><br>   <a href=http://pub97.ezboard.com/fnuclearspacefrm1.showAddReplyScreenFromWeb?topicID=513.topic&index=62>Reply</a>   </td><td valign=top align=left class=m><span class=title>   Re: Interstellar daydreams</span><hr size=1> I'm just posting a brief response here because quite honestly I think anything more would only serve to elicit the same general ideas from me and the same responses back.<br>
<br>
So I just want to clarify an earlier statement made by me:<br>
<br>
I'm not morally objected to using nuclear technologies for space travel.  My moral objections lie in using nuclear BOMBS.<br>
<br>
<br>
Nuclear has been put to enough bad uses on this planet.  I personally think any trip to a new planet, or even star, should involve and new beginning for humanity and relations among different people.  Use it as a unifying factor, bringing together all of humanity.<br>
<br>
I do not think that nuclear bombs being available would aid in this process.  Nor do I think that they have the level of control that is desireable for fully reliable spaceflight.<br>
<br>
I would much rather see a fast-fission reactor witha multi-phase heat capture system, or even an antimatter-fusion or antimatter-fission hybrid reactor.<br>
<br>
Oh, and in the eventuality there is a reactor being used...uh, if volunteers are needed as Reactor Engineers.... well... ::raises hand::  <!--EZCODE EMOTICON START :D --><img src=http://www.ezboard.com/intl/aenglish/images/emoticons/happy.gif ALT=":D"><!--EZCODE EMOTICON END-->  <p></p><i></i></td></tr><tr bgcolor=#484848><td nowrap width=20% valign=top align=left><span class=title> <A HREF=http://pub97.ezboard.com/uyales.showPublicProfile?language=EN>yales</A></span><br> <span class=usertitle>Moderator</span><br>  Posts: 815<br> <font color=#6F6F6F>(9/13/02 1:18:50 pm)</font><br>   <a href=http://pub97.ezboard.com/fnuclearspacefrm1.showAddReplyScreenFromWeb?topicID=513.topic&index=63>Reply</a>   <BR><img src=http://home.attbi.com/~yales/images/53invad2.jpg WIDTH=60 HEIGHT=60></td><td valign=top align=left class=m><span class=title>   Start of a long series...</span><hr size=1> There is much in this thread that requires discussion.<br>
=======================================<br>
Moving back up a bit into the thread...<br>
<br>
We were discussing decontaminating the radioactive environment next to a used Orion pusherplate.<br>
<br>
There was some confusion at this point in the thread. Mauk2 appears (understandably so) to not realize that the thread made an unfortunate abrupt left turn from nuclear thermal engines to nuclear external pulse engines. He brought up the use of aluminum as reactor shielding. <br>
<br>
Getting back on track with the Orion,  I pointed out that the neutron activation AND the embedding of the fission products from a few hundred atomic detonations at about 20 kilotons each at a distance of &lt;100 meters created a non-trivial situation from the point of radiation. <br>
<br>
Zaph thought that yield was too high.<br>
<br>
From the Zaphster:<!--EZCODE QUOTE START--><blockquote><b><i>Quote:</i></b><hr>   Yale,<br>
<br>
You are incorrect...<hr></blockquote><!--EZCODE QUOTE END--><br>
<br>
Z then multiplied my 400 x 20 kt bombs and got 8,000 kilotons total.<br>
<br>
Calculating then for the 4,000 ton Orion in the G. Dyson book, he derived 3,100 kilotons.<br>
<br>
Why the discrepancy? The &quot;base&quot; model Orion typically discussed in this forum is not 4,000 tons, it is 10,000 tons.<br>
<br>
It was the size used by John Fraz in this very thread (post 11)<br>
<br>
Now 4,000 tons is 40% of 10,000 tons.<br>
And not surprisingly, 3,200 kilotons is 40% of 8,000 kilotons.<br>
<br>
Thus, I was, in fact, quite correct. <br>
<br>
We just need to be on the same page as to vehicle size.<br>
<br>
yale<br>
 <p></p><i>Edited by: <A HREF=http://pub97.ezboard.com/uyales.showPublicProfile?language=EN>yales</A> at: 9/13/02 2:11:01 pm<br></i></td></tr><tr bgcolor=#333333><td nowrap width=20% valign=top align=left><span class=title> <A HREF=http://pub97.ezboard.com/uzaphod4468.showPublicProfile?language=EN>zaphod4468</A></span><br> <span class=usertitle>ezOP</span><br>  Posts: 1010<br> <font color=#6F6F6F>(9/13/02 3:22:55 pm)</font><br>   <a href=http://pub97.ezboard.com/fnuclearspacefrm1.showAddReplyScreenFromWeb?topicID=513.topic&index=64>Reply</a>   <BR><img src=http://www.bbc.co.uk/cult/hitchhikers/gallery/images/100/zaphod2.jpg WIDTH=60 HEIGHT=60></td><td valign=top align=left class=m><span class=title>   Re: Start of a long series...</span><hr size=1> I still think your wrong Yalesie,<br>
<br>
It's difficult to discuss one size because Orion scales up so nicely.  I have been talking about the 4,000 ton Orion as I 'indirectly' mention in the 9th post in this thread when I quote a 1000 ton payload, which is what was always estimated for a 4000 ton ground launched Orion.  You were quoting from an interview with F. Dyson that stated 20 kt pulses (I doubt Dyson was aware of John Fraz's post here of a 10,000 ton Orion).  Now, I've read through the Project Orion book (twice) and the most theorized version was the 4000 ton model, not a 10,000 ton model.  It's nit-picking to be sure...  but the 20 kt yield for an Orion pulse is just not right in this instance.<br>
<br>
The MAX yield on the 4000 ton model was 5 kiloton ABOVE 125,000 ft.<br>
<br>
A 10,000 ton Orion is 2.5 times the weight of the 4000 ton version.<br>
<br>
Using K.I.S.S. math - 2.5 x 5 kt = 12.5 kt pulse for a 10,000 ton Orion. <p></p><i></i></td></tr><tr bgcolor=#484848><td nowrap width=20% valign=top align=left><span class=title> <A HREF=http://pub97.ezboard.com/ujohnfraz.showPublicProfile?language=EN>John Fraz</A>&nbsp; <IMG SRC="http://www.ezboard.com/images/posticons/pi_yingyang.gif" BORDER=0></span><br> <span class=usertitle>NERVA Spaceplane Pilot</span><br>  Posts: 205<br> <font color=#6F6F6F>(9/14/02 3:35:52 pm)</font><br>   <a href=http://pub97.ezboard.com/fnuclearspacefrm1.showAddReplyScreenFromWeb?topicID=513.topic&index=65>Reply</a>   <BR><img src=http://lneilsmith.com/tools/littlelogo.gif WIDTH=60 HEIGHT=60></td><td valign=top align=left class=m><span class=title>   Orion: How I learned to love the Bomb</span><hr size=1> I acknowledge that the original purpose of this thread was to discuss NTRs as ground-LEO boosters.<br>
 The inclusion of Orion here is accidental, but interesting.<br>
