<br>
1)You never responded to my main controllability issue, the uncertain yields of nuclear devices.<br>
<br>
2)As far as EMP goes...There would still be EMP effects without atmosphere.  The EMP effects arise from Compton Effect collisions of gammas with any molecule.  In air, this happens to be atmospheric molecules.  On an Orion, you'd have to have the right radiation shielding.  Anything that could have electrons that react with gammas, which is the vast majority of molecules, would create EMP.  Now if there were EMP, you could shield internal systems from it through hardening or metallic shielding of wiring, but that's expensive.  You're left with a very heavy radiation shield to prevent EMP, or an expensive EMP-hardening effort.<br>
<br>
3)Flat out dismissal of a design concern isn't a very godo way to win points in a debate, IMHO.  Nor is patronizing someone by saying they're the equivalent of a silly childhood imagination.  If you disagree with points I make, just state some fact to back up your side, and let the theories be settled by facts and debate. <p></p><i></i></td></tr><tr bgcolor=#333333><td nowrap width=20% valign=top align=left><span class=title> <A HREF=http://pub97.ezboard.com/utim1965.showPublicProfile?language=EN>Tim1965</A></span><br> <span class=usertitle>Space Tourist</span><br>  Posts: 11<br> <font color=#6F6F6F>(9/16/02 3:12:12 am)</font><br>   <a href=http://pub97.ezboard.com/fnuclearspacefrm1.showAddReplyScreenFromWeb?topicID=513.topic&index=70>Reply</a>   </td><td valign=top align=left class=m><span class=title>   Re: Orion is plagued with bogeymen...</span><hr size=1> There are some atomic scaling rules,math formulas,  and some technological techniques that can be used to predict, and control nuclear explosive yields.<br>
