<br>
 I deliberately declined to address it. There are plenty of others here who seem to go into very specific discussion of nuclear engineering &amp; bomb design. I passed the ball to them. It seems to go back to opinion, over whether we (or rather the experts) know enough about bomb design or not.<br>
So we test a bunch of bombs in space to settle the design...<br>
<br>
<!--EZCODE ITALIC START--><i> &gt; <!--EZCODE BOLD START--><b> 2)</b><!--EZCODE BOLD END-->There would still be EMP effects without atmosphere. The EMP effects arise from Compton Effect collisions of gammas with any molecule. In air, this happens to be atmospheric molecules. On an Orion, you'd have to have the right radiation shielding. Anything that could have electrons that react with gammas, which is the vast majority of molecules, would create EMP. Now if there were EMP, you could shield internal systems from it through hardening or metallic shielding of wiring, but that's expensive. You're left with a very heavy radiation shield to prevent EMP, or an expensive EMP-hardening effort.</i><!--EZCODE ITALIC END--><br>
<br>
 Extremely doubtful that it would have any effect. We have a ship structure, and it's is going to throw off EMP (minimally produced from gammas from specially designed tiny bombs) like hundreds of miles of atmosphere and (tens of megatonnes) H-bombs? Isn't a ship's structure of steel going to be a bit less likely to throw off uncontrollable amounts of EMP? Is there any evidence that this is the slightest bit of a show-stopper for Orion?<br>
 So yeah, I'm not being too particular with my evidence chains to support my claims that it's not a big problem. I see it as the detractor's problem, to prove that EMP effect <!--EZCODE ITALIC START--><i>  within the ship</i><!--EZCODE ITALIC END--> (or outside it!) is going to be a problem (to the contrary of the sense of everything we know about EMP).<br>
<br>
<!--EZCODE ITALIC START--><i> <!--EZCODE BOLD START--><b> 3)</b><!--EZCODE BOLD END-->Flat out dismissal of a design concern isn't a very good way to win points in a debate, IMHO.</i><!--EZCODE ITALIC END--><br>
<br>
I challenged anyone to find a shred of proof that it's a problem as much as it was stated to be.<br>
 We contuinually hear about EMP, and never a bit of reason to apply the phenomenon to Orion. Seemingly <!--EZCODE ITALIC START--><i> nothing</i><!--EZCODE ITALIC END--> beyond the chain of reasoning which goes: <!--EZCODE ITALIC START--><i> (nukes produce EMP which is bad. Orion uses nukes. Thusly, Orion must produce EMP which would be bad)</i><!--EZCODE ITALIC END-->.<br>
 It seem pretty clear cut that it shouldn't be considered a problem, and only doubt seemingly without adequate reason supporting that doubt leads it to be brought up against Orion.<br>
<br>
<!--EZCODE ITALIC START--><i> &gt; Nor is patronizing someone by saying they're the equivalent of a silly childhood imagination. If you disagree with points I make, just state some fact to back up your side, and let the theories be settled by facts and debate.</i><!--EZCODE ITALIC END--><br>
<br>
 Sorry that I didn't make it clear that I wasn't attributing the silly complaints against orion to you. Somewhat sorry that I lumped this latest EMP complaint in with all the other silly things we've heard about NPR.<br>
I didn't say that you or your arguments were this silly, I only made allegorical reference to some things we've heard in the past.<br>
<br>
Are pulse unit bombs going to produce enough of an EMP effect from compton effect scattering of gammas from electrons <!--EZCODE ITALIC START--><i> in steel</i><!--EZCODE ITALIC END-->, to produce a problem for ship's electronics systems designers?<br>
<br>
<br>
