<br>
 For a start, take your design and the proofs to the <!--EZCODE LINK START--><a href="http://groups.yahoo.com/group/Know_Nukes/">Know-Nukes</a><!--EZCODE LINK END--> list at Yahell.<br>
<br>
I'd love to see some feasible designs come about from interactions on lists like this. It'd be a real accomplishment for nuclearspace.com.<br>
(next, write it up for a presentation to AIAA...) <p></p><i></i></td></tr><tr bgcolor=#484848><td nowrap width=20% valign=top align=left><span class=title> <A HREF=http://pub97.ezboard.com/uarkuunaves.showPublicProfile?language=EN>ArkuunAves</A></span><br> <span class=usertitle>NERVA Spaceplane Pilot</span><br>  Posts: 113<br> <font color=#6F6F6F>(9/20/02 3:58:52 pm)</font><br>   <a href=http://pub97.ezboard.com/fnuclearspacefrm1.showAddReplyScreenFromWeb?topicID=513.topic&index=79>Reply</a>   </td><td valign=top align=left class=m><span class=title>   Re: Put your money where your mouth is...</span><hr size=1> :: blinks ::<br>
<br>
At what point did we state this spaceship is going to be steel?<br>
<br>
I am the only one seeing a possible problem with this?  Steel is a rather high-mass solution to things, considering composites are used for just about everything in space nowadays.<br>
<br>
You'd be looking at an incredible loss of thrust efficiency even going to steel...<br>
<br>
<br>
But if you want to go with steel(I have no clue why you would want to), what kind?  There are literally hundreds of types, each of which will interact different with gammas.  And steel in and of itself is not that amazing of a radiation shield, bear in mind; you'd need <!--EZCODE ITALIC START--><i>  several</i><!--EZCODE ITALIC END--> inches of stainless steel to even begin to shield it.  Please also bear in mind this is gamma radiation, not alpha or beta which doesn't have very high energies.<br>
<br>
Steel DOES corrode in the presence of gamma radiation, please realize; it is one of the key issues in a nuclear power plant.  Stainless steel holds up better than most other kinds of things, but it's not by any means impervious.<br>
<br>
<br>
<br>
I think this is just a good example of things here.  I agree with your call for specific designs.  And when it comes to designs, it is the responsibility of the person with the design concept to come up with a mockup and scientific basis for it.  It is <!--EZCODE ITALIC START--><i>  not</i><!--EZCODE ITALIC END--> the responsibility of others to prove the idea <!--EZCODE ITALIC START--><i>  wrong</i><!--EZCODE ITALIC END-->.<br>
<br>
You ask me for numbers? I don't have empirical data specific to pulse-bomb propulsion of a spacecraft to be able to state things either way...do you?  All I can go by is known data and models, and most of these suggest to me that a pulse-bomb propelled spacecraft, while feasible, would not be as cost- and safety-efficient as a craft powered by other nuclear means.<br>
<br>
At some point you have to take into account the number of unknowns.  Simply saying &quot;well....this is possible!&quot; isn't a good reason to try it if there's a 70% chance of failure in a project involving billions of dollars and nuclear explosions. <p></p><i>Edited by: <A HREF=http://pub97.ezboard.com/uarkuunaves.showPublicProfile?language=EN>ArkuunAves</A> at: 9/20/02 3:59:20 pm<br></i></td></tr><tr bgcolor=#333333><td nowrap width=20% valign=top align=left><span class=title> <A HREF=http://pub97.ezboard.com/bnuclearspace.showLocalUserPublicProfile?login=brucetrib>brucetrib</A></span><br> <span class=usertitle>NEP Freighter Crewman</span><br>  Posts: 81<br> <font color=#6F6F6F>(9/20/02 7:26:03 pm)</font><br>   <a href=http://pub97.ezboard.com/fnuclearspacefrm1.showAddReplyScreenFromWeb?topicID=513.topic&index=80>Reply</a>   </td><td valign=top align=left class=m><span class=title> <img src="http://www.nuclearspace.com/ezboard/images/posticons/16.gif" align=absmiddle>  Risk of happening please.</span><hr size=1> Engine Destruct System Development:<br>
<br>
&quot;The requirements for an engine destruct system, to counter the random reentry problem associated with failures of nuclear spacecraft, was discussed.<br>
<br>
The fact, that typical nuclear rocket reactor core materials consist of high temperature refractory materials, is indicative that large intact masses of core materials will survive the reentry heating environment to impact on the Earth's surface.<br>
The optimum means for disposing of a radioactive reentry body is to resolve it into fine particulate debris which will be dispersed and retained by the upper atmosphere. Reactor debris injected in this manner will have a mean residence time from 6 months to several years, so that radioactive decay during stratosphere residence will reduce the resultant ground concentration from fallout to undetectable levels.<br>
<br>
Alternate conceptual means for effecting safe disposal of nuclear rocket reactor include:<br>
<br>
Thermochemical Destruct<br>
Nuclear Destruct<br>
Explosive Destruct<br>
Metallurgical additives.&quot;<br>
<br>
Atmosphere: &quot;...Currently, the consensus of opinion is that nuclear rocket debris injected as fine particulates will come under the influence of the same fallout mechanism and will be completely masked by fallout from nuclear weapons debris now existing in the atmosphere.&quot;<br>
<br>
<br>
All these countermeasures were experimented; remember way back when...<br>
<br>
<br>
Frankly the &quot;Chemical brothers&quot; can have their system operate under 50 miles no big deal I guess till other dead lift methods overtake Chemical.<br>
<br>
But currently, orbital lifetimes as a function of altitude is being worked.<br>
<br>
&quot;Example: an 82kg/m2 spacecraft (e.g. An 8200kg FEP vehicle with 100 m2 of frontal area) placed in a 550 km orbit is estimated to require 20 months to re-enter the same craft placed 600km orbit would require 9 years, orbits of 700km and higher all have lifetimes greater than 10 years.&quot; For the decay on some nuke fuels. By the time it hits the ground you could scoop some of the particulate and sprinkle some on your hotdogs for a backyard cookout.<br>
<br>
Also, check out a study done by Rob Edwards, &quot;How did uranium get into space&quot;.<br>
<br>
Apart from man made outer space sources Supernovae are isotope manufacturing machines and you could add violent volcanic eruptions.<br>
<br>
Lastly, a nuke rocket accidental explosion is a one time event it would not occur over and over again; unless the engineers where chronic stupids...Ha !!<br>
<br>
*Operational safety of nuclear rockets: George P. Dix<br>
*Potential Operating Orbits for Fission Electric Propulsion:<br>
Houts,Kos,Poston.<br>
